{"id":"2207.05158","submitter":"Ding-Fang Zeng","authors":"Ding-fang Zeng","title":"Gravity Induced Spontaneous Radiation","comments":"9 pages, 6 figures, version appearing on Nucl.Phys.B","journal-ref":"Nucl.Phys.B990(May.2023)116171","doi":"10.1016/j.nuclphysb.2023.116171","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We suggest that behind the black hole information paradox is a new and\nuniversal radiation mechanism, Gravity Induced Spontaneous Radiation, or GISR\nhereafter. This mechanism happens to all kinds of compositional objects and it\nrequires only their microscopic structure as the basis. It's always accompanied\nwith such inner structures' variation and allows for explicitly hermitian\nhamiltonian description. For black holes, by Wigner-Wiesskopf approximation we\nshow that such a radiation has a thermal spectrum exactly the same as hawking\nradiation; while through numeric integration, we show that the variation of the\nradiation particles' entropy exhibits all features of Page curve as expected.\nWe also provide exact and analytic solutions to the Einstein equation\ndescribing microscopic structures required by the GISR of black holes and show\nthat, after quantisation the degeneracy of wave functions corresponding with\nthose solutions are consistent with the area law formula of Bekenstein-Hawking\nentropy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 2 Jul 2022 18:57:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 15 Aug 2022 00:49:54 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 4 Feb 2023 12:04:11 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 4 Apr 2023 14:12:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-05"}
